ols to continue to improve the health of LGBTQ2S people. Written by expert authors, many with lived experiences, this fully updated version builds on the critically praised first edition and highlights the significant social, medical, and legal progress that has occurred in Canada since 2003. The book includes general medical information, and guidance that is useful for anyone providing care to LGBTQ2S people. Chapters begin with the fundamentals of language, cultural competency, and the patient-provider relationship. This edition includes contemporary and expanded chapters on STIs, HIV, substance use, mental health, fertility, and trans health, and concludes with unique considerations for those who experience an intersection of diverse identities. Written for a general and trainee-level reader in health care and primary care, this clinical guide provides a comprehensive understanding of LGBTQ2S health.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh  aLGBT.  aLGBTQ.  aLGBTQ2S.  acare.  agay.  ahealth.  alesbian.  amarginalized.  amedicine.  aqueer health.  atrans.  avulnerable.1 aArmstrong, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourns, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourns, Amy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCoutin, Alexandre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFairgrieve, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGahagan, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeller, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodridge, Jordan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHardy, Zongwe Binesikwe Crystal, ec